<DOC><DOCNO> ZF310-643-614 </DOCNO><DOCID>10 643 614.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Newsbytes  April 22 1991* Full Text COPYRIGHT Newsbytes Inc. 1991.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>New York Times focuses on hackers.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>McMullen, Barbara E.; McMullen, John F.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Computer hackersLegal IssuesComputer crimes.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>****NEW YORK TIMES FOCUSES ON HACKERS 04/22/91 NEW YORK, NEW YORK, U.S.A.,andO;1991 APR 22 (NB) -- The New York Times of Sunday, April 21 contains two majorstories involving those computer users often referred to as 'hackers.'andM;The `New York Times Magazine' section of the paper features a five page pieceenitled: `In Defense of Hackers' by Craig Bromberg, which details thefounding and activities of the Electronic Frontier Foundation (EFF).andP;  Itfocuses on EFF co-founder John Perry Barlow and traces the incidents whichled up to his joining with Mitchell Kapor to found the organization.andM;A news feature in section 1 of the paper entitled `Computer Intruders TappingU.S.andP;  Systems With Immunity,' by John Markoff, relates a story of repeatedintrusions into United States computer systems by a group of Dutch nationals.andM;According to the story, the group has entered into computers at the KennedySpace Center, the Pentagon's Pacific Fleet Command, the Lawrence LivermoreNational Laboratory and Stanford University.andP;  The article states that thegroup is able to continue these activities because Netherlands law doesn'tforbid such intrusions.andM;The article further describes the appearance of one of the group on a Dutchtelevision show in February in which, with his back to the camera, he brokeinto what he claimed was a U.S.andP;  military computer holding missile testinformation.andM;Emmanuel Goldstein, editor of 2600 Magazine: The Hacker Quarterly, commentedon the Times articles to Newsbytes, saying: &quot;The pieces were interesting buta bit confusing.andP;  I don't see what the news was in the Dutch case.andP;  I'veknown for a good while that this was going on.andP;  As for the other piece, itclearly gives the impression that EFF is a hacker's defense fund -- somethingthat it has constantly said that it is not.andP;  &quot;andM;Goldstein, speaking about the alleged Dutch intrusions, said: &quot;We should notbe forcing our laws on the Dutch.andP;  If we wish our computer systems to besecure, we should make them secure.andP;  If the Dutch wish to have open systems,that is up to them -- and can work to our advantage.andP;  They tell us what theyare doing and criminals don't do that.&quot;andM;Gail Thackeray, quoted in the Times article as critical of the non-existenceof Dutch laws, told Newsbytes that the absence of laws in other countriescauses problems: &quot;Countries will usually not extradite people for trial inother counties if the actions that they have supposedly committed are notcriminal in the host country or if the possible penalties for the crime areconsidered out of line by that country,&quot; he said.andM;&quot;For example, Canada does not have the death penalty and it will notextradite persons to the United States for crimes for which the death penaltymight be applicable.andP;  Countries with existing computer law will be moreunderstanding of our law,&quot; he added.andM;Thackeray also commented on Goldstein's statement that it is up to us to makeour systems secure.andP;  &quot;That sounds fine but the systems mentioned in thearticle as broken into are government and educational ones.andP;  Should ourtaxpayers have to pay for enhanced security to keep some Dutch citizens fromintruding?&quot; he said.andM;(Barbara E. McMullen andamp; John F. McMullen/19910422)</TEXT></DOC>